1	1000	1	1	How the web works	TEXT	<h2>Clients, servers, and HTTP</h2>\n<p>When you visit a website, your <strong>browser</strong> (the client) sends an HTTP request to a <strong>server</strong>. The server responds with HTML, CSS, JavaScript, images, and other assets. The browser parses HTML into the DOM, applies CSS, and runs JavaScript.</p>\n<ul>\n  <li><strong>HTML</strong> — structure and meaning</li>\n  <li><strong>CSS</strong> — presentation and layout</li>\n  <li><strong>JavaScript</strong> — behavior and interactivity</li>\n</ul>\n<p>In this course you will master the first two pillars before moving on to JavaScript in the next course.</p>	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	0	t	2026-05-25 11:28:44.928	\N
2	1000	1	1	Developer environment setup	TEXT	<h2>Tools you need</h2>\n<ol>\n  <li>Install <a href="https://code.visualstudio.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">VS Code</a> or your preferred editor.</li>\n  <li>Use a modern browser with DevTools (Chrome, Firefox, or Edge).</li>\n  <li>Create a project folder and open it in your editor.</li>\n  <li>Optional: install the Live Server extension for instant reload.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Create <code>index.html</code>, open it in the browser, and verify you can edit and refresh. You are ready to code.</p>	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	1	t	2026-05-25 11:28:44.933	\N
3	1000	1	1	Introduction to HTML	VIDEO	<p>Watch this overview of HTML tags, attributes, and document structure. After the video, create a page with <code>&lt;header&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;main&gt;</code>, and <code>&lt;footer&gt;</code>.</p>	https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qz0aGYrrlhU	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	2	t	2026-05-25 11:28:44.955	\N
4	1000	1	2	Semantic HTML elements	TEXT	<h2>Write HTML that machines and humans understand</h2>\n<p>Prefer semantic elements instead of nesting many <code>&lt;div&gt;</code>s without meaning:</p>\n<pre>&lt;article&gt;\n  &lt;h1&gt;Blog post title&lt;/h1&gt;\n  &lt;p&gt;Published &lt;time datetime="2026-05-01"&gt;May 1, 2026&lt;/time&gt;&lt;/p&gt;\n  &lt;p&gt;Article body…&lt;/p&gt;\n&lt;/article&gt;</pre>\n<p>Use <code>&lt;nav&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;section&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;aside&gt;</code>, and heading levels (<code>h1</code>–<code>h6</code>) consistently for SEO and screen readers.</p>	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	0	t	2026-05-25 11:28:44.961	\N
5	1000	1	2	Forms and user input	TEXT	<h2>Collecting data in the browser</h2>\n<p>Forms use <code>&lt;form&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;label&gt;</code>, and input types (<code>text</code>, <code>email</code>, <code>password</code>, <code>checkbox</code>, <code>radio</code>, <code>select</code>).</p>\n<ul>\n  <li>Always associate labels with inputs via <code>for</code> / <code>id</code>.</li>\n  <li>Use <code>required</code>, <code>pattern</code>, and <code>minlength</code> for client-side validation.</li>\n  <li>Set <code>name</code> attributes — they become field names when the form is submitted.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Exercise:</strong> Build a contact form with name, email, message, and a submit button.</p>	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	1	t	2026-05-25 11:28:44.968	\N
6	1000	1	2	Accessibility essentials	TEXT	<h2>Build for everyone</h2>\n<ul>\n  <li>One <code>h1</code> per page; headings in order.</li>\n  <li>Alt text on images that convey information.</li>\n  <li>Sufficient color contrast (WCAG AA: 4.5:1 for body text).</li>\n  <li>Keyboard navigation: focus styles visible on links and buttons.</li>\n  <li>Use <code>aria-label</code> only when visible text is not possible.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Test with Tab key only — can you reach every interactive element?</p>	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	2	t	2026-05-25 11:28:44.971	\N
7	1000	1	3	Selectors and the cascade	TEXT	<h2>How CSS applies styles</h2>\n<p>Specificity order: inline styles → IDs → classes/attributes → elements. Later rules win when specificity is equal.</p>\n<pre>/* Class + element */\n.card h2 { color: #1e40af; }\n\n/* Pseudo-class */\na:hover { text-decoration: underline; }</pre>\n<p>Use class names (BEM or utility-style) instead of deep nesting. Keep styles reusable.</p>	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	0	t	2026-05-25 11:28:44.977	\N
8	1000	1	3	Flexbox layout	VIDEO	<p>Flexbox is ideal for navigation bars, card rows, and vertical centering. Practice: build a header with logo left and menu links right using <code>display: flex</code> and <code>justify-content: space-between</code>.</p>	https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fYq5PXgSsbE	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	1	t	2026-05-25 11:28:44.98	\N
9	1000	1	3	CSS Grid for page layouts	TEXT	<h2>Two-dimensional layouts</h2>\n<pre>.page {\n  display: grid;\n  grid-template-columns: 240px 1fr;\n  grid-template-rows: auto 1fr auto;\n  min-height: 100vh;\n}</pre>\n<p>Combine Grid for page structure with Flexbox for components inside cells. Use <code>gap</code> instead of margins between grid items.</p>	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	2	t	2026-05-25 11:28:44.993	\N
10	1000	1	4	Mobile-first CSS	TEXT	<h2>Start small, enhance for larger screens</h2>\n<p>Write base styles for mobile, then add breakpoints with <code>@media (min-width: …)</code>.</p>\n<pre>@media (min-width: 768px) {\n  .grid { grid-template-columns: repeat(2, 1fr); }\n}</pre>\n<p>Use relative units: <code>rem</code> for typography, <code>%</code> and <code>fr</code> for layout, <code>max-width</code> on containers (~1200px).</p>	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	0	t	2026-05-25 11:28:45.006	\N
11	1000	1	4	Responsive images & media queries workshop	TEXT	<h2>Adapt content to viewport</h2>\n<pre>&lt;img src="hero-800.jpg" srcset="hero-400.jpg 400w, hero-800.jpg 800w, hero-1200.jpg 1200w" sizes="(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 50vw" alt="Team collaborating" /&gt;</pre>\n<p><strong>Project:</strong> Convert a fixed-width landing page to a responsive layout with a collapsible mobile nav.</p>	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	1	t	2026-05-25 11:28:45.014	\N
12	1000	1	4	CSS reference cheat sheet	PDF	<p>Download and keep this reference nearby while building layouts. Review Flexbox and Grid property lists weekly.</p>	https://www.w3.org/WAI/ER/tests/xhtml/testfiles/resources/pdf/dummy.pdf	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	2	t	2026-05-25 11:28:45.017	\N
13	1000	2	5	Variables, types, and operators	TEXT	<h2>JavaScript building blocks</h2>\n<p>Use <code>const</code> by default, <code>let</code> when reassignment is needed. Avoid <code>var</code>.</p>\n<pre>const price = 19.99;\nlet quantity = 1;\nquantity += 1;\n\nconst label = `Total: $${(price * quantity).toFixed(2)}`;</pre>\n<p>Primitive types: <code>string</code>, <code>number</code>, <code>boolean</code>, <code>null</code>, <code>undefined</code>, <code>bigint</code>, <code>symbol</code>. Objects and arrays are reference types.</p>	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	0	t	2026-05-25 11:28:45.044	\N
14	1000	2	5	Functions and scope	TEXT	<h2>Reusable logic</h2>\n<pre>function greet(name) {\n  return `Hello, ${name}`;\n}\n\nconst double = (n) => n * 2;</pre>\n<p>Understand block scope, closures (functions that remember outer variables), and arrow functions for callbacks.</p>	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	1	t	2026-05-25 11:28:45.047	\N
15	1000	2	5	Control flow and arrays	VIDEO	<p>Practice <code>if/else</code>, <code>for…of</code>, and array methods: <code>map</code>, <code>filter</code>, <code>reduce</code>, <code>find</code>.</p>	https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=W6NZfZ5FjY8	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	2	t	2026-05-25 11:28:45.054	\N
16	1000	2	6	Selecting and updating the DOM	TEXT	<h2>JavaScript meets HTML</h2>\n<pre>const btn = document.querySelector('#submit');\nconst list = document.querySelectorAll('.item');\n\nbtn.addEventListener('click', () =&gt; {\n  list.forEach(el =&gt; el.classList.toggle('done'));\n});</pre>\n<p>Prefer <code>textContent</code> over <code>innerHTML</code> for user data to prevent XSS.</p>	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	0	t	2026-05-25 11:28:45.058	\N
17	1000	2	6	Event delegation & forms in JS	TEXT	<h2>Handle dynamic content efficiently</h2>\n<p>Attach one listener on a parent and inspect <code>event.target</code> instead of binding every row.</p>\n<p>On form submit: call <code>event.preventDefault()</code>, read values with <code>FormData</code>, validate, then update the UI or call an API.</p>	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	1	t	2026-05-25 11:28:45.06	\N
18	1000	2	7	Promises and async/await	TEXT	<h2>Non-blocking code</h2>\n<pre>async function loadUsers() {\n  const res = await fetch('/api/users');\n  if (!res.ok) throw new Error('Request failed');\n  return res.json();\n}</pre>\n<p>Always handle errors with <code>try/catch</code>. Show loading and error states in the UI.</p>	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	0	t	2026-05-25 11:28:45.073	\N
19	1000	2	7	Working with REST APIs	TEXT	<h2>Fetch JSON from a server</h2>\n<p>Typical CRUD flow: GET list → render → POST create → PATCH update → DELETE remove.</p>\n<p><strong>Exercise:</strong> Build a todo list that loads from <code>jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/todos</code> and displays loading/error/empty states.</p>	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	1	t	2026-05-25 11:28:45.075	\N
20	1000	3	8	Components, props, and JSX	TEXT	<h2>UI as a function of state</h2>\n<pre>function Greeting({ name }) {\n  return &lt;h1&gt;Hello, {name}&lt;/h1&gt;;\n}</pre>\n<p>Break UIs into small, reusable components. Pass data down via props; keep components pure when possible.</p>	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	0	t	2026-05-25 11:28:45.095	\N
